{"id":"quant-ph/0508038","submitter":"Paul Benioff","authors":"Paul Benioff (Argonne National Laboratory, Argonne, IL.)","title":"Complex Rational Numbers in Quantum Mechanics","comments":"12 pages Contribution for Proceedings, ISSUR-05, in Int. Jour. Mod.\n  Physics, B","journal-ref":"International Journal of Modern Physics B Vol 20, 1730-1741 (2006)","doi":"10.1142/S021797920603425X","report-no":null,"categories":"quant-ph","license":null,"abstract":"  A binary representation of complex rational numbers and their arithmetic is\ndescribed that is not based on qubits. It takes account of the fact that $0s$\nin a qubit string do not contribute to the value of a number. They serve only\nas place holders. The representation is based on the distribution of four types\nof systems, corresponding to $+1,-1,+i,-i,$ along an integer lattice. Complex\nrational numbers correspond to arbitrary products of four types of creation\noperators acting on the vacuum state. An occupation number representation is\ngiven for both bosons and fermions.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Wed, 3 Aug 2005 21:18:35 GMT"}],"update_date":"2007-05-23"}
